We need to define a functorial action of G on morphisms d\xrightarrow {k}d'\in    D. By naturality of the specified isomorphisms, for the assignment Gk to
  be functorial, the diagram 




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
      C(-, Gd)\ar [r, leftrightarrow]\ar [d, "Gk_*"'] & D(F-, d)\ar [d, "k_*"] \\
      C(-, Gd')\ar [r, leftrightarrow] & D(F-, d')
    \end {tikzcd}


must commute. The composite map C(-, Gd)\cong  D(F-, d)\xrightarrow {k^*} D(F-,   d')\cong  C(-, Gd') is a natural transformation, hence by the Yoneda
  lemma corresponds to a unique map Gd\xrightarrow {Gk} Gd'. This
  establishes uniqueness; it remains to show functorality, but since these
  diagrams defining Gk paste vertically, the composites (Gk)(Gk') satisfy
  the given construction, hence uniqueness guarantees that G is functorial.

